{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535586"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:58:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:58:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15491"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15491"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.2,0.11,0.15,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8182"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89882"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8182"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15491"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74051"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"205"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"},{"type":"tags","id":"1936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"8978"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19811"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30613"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44606"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89882"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine occupational health check. He has worked as a welder for the past 30 years and has no significant medical history. He does not take any regular medications. He is an ex-smoker with a 15 pack-year history, having quit five years ago. He reports mild shortness of breath on moderate exertion but is otherwise well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Chest examination reveals normal breath sounds with good air entry bilaterally. A chest X-ray shows small, ill-defined nodular opacities throughout the middle and lower lung zones with areas of coarse reticular shadowing. Spirometry results are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Siderosis","Berylliosis","Coal worker\u0027s pneumoconiosis","Asbestosis","Silicosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s occupational history as a welder, combined with the radiological findings and relatively mild symptoms, is most consistent with siderosis. Siderosis is caused by the inhalation of iron oxide fumes or dust, commonly encountered in welding work. It is considered a benign pneumoconiosis as it typically causes minimal functional impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESiderosis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by chest X-ray changes showing small, ill-defined nodular opacities and coarse reticular shadowing predominantly in the middle and lower lung zones. Despite these impressive radiological findings, pulmonary function tests often remain normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoal worker\u0027s pneumoconiosis\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in coal miners and typically presents with more significant symptoms and functional impairment. The radiological appearance would show upper zone predominant nodular opacities, and there is no history of coal mine exposure in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESilicosis\u003C/strong\u003E results from crystalline silica exposure, commonly seen in mining, quarrying, and sandblasting. It typically causes more severe symptoms and distinctive upper lobe nodular opacities with possible hilar lymphadenopathy. This patient\u0027s occupation and presentation do not fit with silicosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsbestosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with lower lobe predominant reticular changes and pleural plaques on chest X-ray. It is associated with asbestos exposure in construction or shipyard work, which is not part of this patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBerylliosis\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by beryllium exposure in electronics and aerospace industries. It causes granulomatous inflammation similar to sarcoidosis and typically presents with more severe symptoms and distinctive radiological findings including hilar lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Siderosis is an occupational lung disease caused by chronic inhalation of iron dust or fumes.","Chest X-ray findings in siderosis typically show ill-defined nodules or reticular opacities in middle and lower lung zones.","Occupational history and relatively mild symptoms despite impressive radiological findings are key diagnostic features of siderosis."],"references":["Doherty MJ, Healy M, Richardson SG, et al. Total body iron overload in welder\u2019s siderosis. Occupational and Environmental Medicine 2004;61:82-85.","Pulmonary siderosis [Internet]. Gpnotebook.com. 2018 [cited 2024 Nov 15]. Available at: https://gpnotebook.com/en-AU/pages/respiratory-and-chest-medicine/pulmonary-siderosis\u200c","Pulmonary haemosiderosis. Radiopaedia. Internet webpage. [cited 2025 Mar 11] Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/pulmonary-haemosiderosis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74051"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15491"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74051"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T13:37:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T13:37:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8182"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89882"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings